        "content": "<p>If the type of a theorem has an elaboration error and the proof of the theorem has a parse error, the elaboration error is not shown. This often causes beginners to think that there is no error in the type of a theorem.</p>\n<p>Example: in each of these theorems the type is nonsense and should show an error, but doesn't.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">foo1</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span> <span class=\"mi\">4</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">simp</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">foo2</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span> <span class=\"mi\">4</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">sim</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">foo3</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span> <span class=\"mi\">4</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">foo4</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span> <span class=\"mi\">4</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">foo5</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span> <span class=\"mi\">4</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">constructor</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">Â·</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
